Requirements¶

SHAP: Download the repo from https://github.com/castillohair/shap and install the version in the branch genomics_mod. The following commands can be run in a terminal to achieve this:

pip uninstall shap # uninstall previous version of shap if there is one
git clone https://github.com/castillohair/shap # download SHAP
cd shap
git checkout castillohair/genomics_mod # switch to appropriate branch
python setup.py install

Other libraries required are deeplift and logomaker which should be installed normally through pip or conda.

Load model¶

Here we load three models trained on different sets of chromosomes. We then make a model whose output is the average of the three individual models.

In [2]:
max_seq_len = 500
In [3]:
# Load models
chr_splits_idx = [0, 1, 2]
model_input = layers.Input(shape=(max_seq_len, 4))
model_list = []
model_outputs = []
for chr_split_idx in chr_splits_idx:
    print(f"Loading model {chr_split_idx}...")
    model_split = resnet.load_model(
        f'resnet_chr_split_{chr_split_idx}_w_mse_0.5_w_pearsonr_0.5_continued.h5'
    )
    model_split._name = f'model_chr_split_{chr_split_idx}'
    model_list.append(model_split)

    model_output = model_split(model_input)
    model_outputs.append(model_output)

# Model output: average of bs model outputs
model_avg_output = layers.Average()(model_outputs)

model_avg = models.Model(
    model_input,
    model_avg_output,
    )

model_avg

# Predict just to check sequence

# 95 predictions correspond to the log10 atac peak signal of each cell state
seqs_onehot = seq_utils.one_hot_encode([seq], max_seq_len=max_seq_len)
preds = model_avg.predict(seqs_onehot)
preds.shape

# Plot predictions
fig, ax = pyplot.subplots(figsize=(14, 5))
seaborn.barplot(
    x=cell_states,
    y=preds[0],
    ax=ax,
)
ax.set_xticklabels(cell_states, rotation=90)
ax.set_ylabel('log10(ATAC peak signal)')

One cell state¶

In [ ]:
# Calculate contributions for one cell state
# Contributions are an array of max_seq_len x 4
# Contributions on this version of SHAP are such that
# numpy.sum(seq_contribs*seq_onehot, axis=1) will
# return the nucleotide contributions on each base
cell_state = 'evl(30epi)'
seq_contribs = interpret.compute_contribution_scores(
    seq,
    model_avg,
    cell_state,
    cell_states_all=cell_states,
)
seq_contribs.shape

In [ ]:
# Calculate contributions for multiple cell states and plot
cell_states_to_plot = [
    'evl(30epi)',
    'evl(75epi)',
    'evl(6somite)',
]
seq_contribs_dict = {}

# calculate contributions
for cell_state in cell_states_to_plot:
    seq_contribs = interpret.compute_contribution_scores(
        seq,
        model_avg,
        cell_state,
        cell_states_all=cell_states,
    )
    seq_contribs_dict[cell_state] = seq_contribs

# plot
custom_plots.plot_seq_and_contributions(
    seq,
    seq_contribs_dict,
    cell_states_to_plot,
);
